			<div class="gallerytext">The first scientific explorations in Persepolis were conducted by <a href="/wiki/Ernst_Herzfeld" title="Ernst Herzfeld">Ernst Herzfeld</a> in 1931</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 92.666666666667px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 90.666666666667px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Persepolis_Colonne_flandin.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="The design and details of the columns of Persepolis"><img alt="The design and details of the columns of Persepolis" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Persepolis_Colonne_flandin.jpg/136px-Persepolis_Colonne_flandin.jpg" decoding="async" width="91" height="120" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Persepolis_Colonne_flandin.jpg/204px-Persepolis_Colonne_flandin.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Persepolis_Colonne_flandin.jpg/272px-Persepolis_Colonne_flandin.jpg 2x" data-file-width="641" data-file-height="849" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">The design and details of the columns of Persepolis</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 314px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 312px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Persepolis_Rec_Iso_Toit_Tach_Chipiez.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="Roof design of palaces at Persepolis"><img alt="Roof design of palaces at Persepolis" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Persepolis_Rec_Iso_Toit_Tach_Chipiez.jpg/468px-Persepolis_Rec_Iso_Toit_Tach_Chipiez.jpg" decoding="async" width="312" height="120" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Persepolis_Rec_Iso_Toit_Tach_Chipiez.jpg/701px-Persepolis_Rec_Iso_Toit_Tach_Chipiez.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Persepolis_Rec_Iso_Toit_Tach_Chipiez.jpg/935px-Persepolis_Rec_Iso_Toit_Tach_Chipiez.jpg 2x" data-file-width="960" data-file-height="370" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">Roof design of palaces at Persepolis</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 252px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 250px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Chipiez_100_colonnes.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="The design of the Thorne Hall, Persepolis"><img alt="The design of the Thorne Hall, Persepolis" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Chipiez_100_colonnes.jpg/375px-Chipiez_100_colonnes.jpg" decoding="async" width="250" height="120" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Chipiez_100_colonnes.jpg/562px-Chipiez_100_colonnes.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/10/Chipiez_100_colonnes.jpg 2x" data-file-width="640" data-file-height="308" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">The design of the Thorne Hall, Persepolis</div>
		</li>
</ul>
<p>The fruitful region was covered with villages until its frightful devastation in the 18th century; and even now it is, comparatively speaking, well cultivated. The Castle of Estakhr played a conspicuous part as a strong fortress, several times, during the Muslim period. It was the middlemost and the highest of the three steep crags which rise from the valley of the <a href="/wiki/Kur" class="mw-redirect" title="Kur">Kur</a>, at some distance to the west or northwest of the necropolis of <a href="/wiki/Naqsh-e_Rustam" class="mw-redirect" title="Naqsh-e Rustam">Naqsh-e Rustam</a>.
</p><p>The French voyagers <a href="/wiki/Eug%C3%A8ne_Flandin" title="Eugène Flandin">Eugène Flandin</a> and <a href="/wiki/Pascal_Coste" title="Pascal Coste">Pascal Coste</a> are among the first to provide not only a literary review of the structure of Persepolis, but also to create some of the best and earliest visual depictions of its structure. In their publications in Paris, in 1881 and 1882, titled <span title="French-language text"><i lang="fr">Voyages en Perse de MM. Eugene Flanin peintre et Pascal Coste architecte</i></span>, the authors provided some 350 ground breaking illustrations of Persepolis.<sup id="cite_ref-ali_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ali-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup> French influence and interest in Persia's archaeological findings continued after the accession of <a href="/wiki/Reza_Shah" title="Reza Shah">Reza Shah</a>, when <a href="/wiki/Andr%C3%A9_Godard" title="André Godard">André Godard</a> became the first director of the archeological service of Iran.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 1800s, a variety of amateur digging occurred at the site, in some cases on a large scale.<sup id="cite_ref-ali_33-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ali-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The first scientific excavations at Persepolis were carried out by <a href="/wiki/Ernst_Herzfeld" title="Ernst Herzfeld">Ernst Herzfeld</a> and <a href="/wiki/Erich_Schmidt_(archaeologist)" title="Erich Schmidt (archaeologist)">Erich Schmidt</a> representing the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Chicago_Oriental_Institute" class="mw-redirect" title="University of Chicago Oriental Institute">Oriental Institute</a> of the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Chicago" title="University of Chicago">University of Chicago</a>. They conducted excavations for eight seasons, beginning in 1930, and included other nearby sites.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Persian_frieze_designs_at_Persepolis.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/Persian_frieze_designs_at_Persepolis.jpg/220px-Persian_frieze_designs_at_Persepolis.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="164" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/Persian_frieze_designs_at_Persepolis.jpg/330px-Persian_frieze_designs_at_Persepolis.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/Persian_frieze_designs_at_Persepolis.jpg/440px-Persian_frieze_designs_at_Persepolis.jpg 2x" data-file-width="746" data-file-height="555" /></a><figcaption><a href="/wiki/Frieze" title="Frieze">Frieze</a> designs at Persepolis</figcaption></figure>
<p>Herzfeld believed that the reasons behind the construction of Persepolis were the need for a majestic atmosphere, a symbol for the empire, and to celebrate special events, especially the <i><a href="/wiki/Nowruz" title="Nowruz">Nowruz</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-wood_7-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wood-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> For historical reasons, Persepolis was built where the Achaemenid dynasty was founded, although it was not the center of the empire at that time.
</p><p>Excavations of plaque fragments hint at a scene with a contest between <a href="/wiki/Herakles" class="mw-redirect" title="Herakles">Herakles</a> and <a href="/wiki/Apollo" title="Apollo">Apollo</a>, dubbed <i>A Greek painting at Persepolis</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Architecture">Architecture</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Persepolis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Architecture"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Persepolitan architecture is noted for its use of the <a href="/wiki/Persian_column" title="Persian column">Persian column</a>, which was probably based on earlier wooden columns.
</p><p>The buildings at Persepolis include three general groupings: military quarters, the treasury, and the reception halls and occasional houses for the King. Noted structures include the Great Stairway, the <a href="/wiki/Gate_of_All_Nations" title="Gate of All Nations">Gate of All Nations</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Apadana" title="Apadana">Apadana</a>, the Hall of a Hundred Columns, the Tripylon Hall and the <a href="/wiki/Tachara" title="Tachara">Tachara</a>, the Hadish Palace, the Palace of <a href="/wiki/Artaxerxes_III" title="Artaxerxes III">Artaxerxes III</a>, the Imperial Treasury, the Royal Stables, and the Chariot House.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Remains">Remains</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Persepolis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Remains"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div style="float: left; clear: left;">
