<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="The_Gate_of_All_Nations">The Gate of All Nations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Persepolis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: The Gate of All Nations"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Gate_of_All_Nations" title="Gate of All Nations">Gate of All Nations</a></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:The_stone_columns_of_the_Gate_of_All_Nations,_they_were_16%C2%BD_meters_high_and_were_topped_with_capitals_in_the_form_of_a_double_bull,_Persepolis,_Iran_(47779521811).jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/The_stone_columns_of_the_Gate_of_All_Nations%2C_they_were_16%C2%BD_meters_high_and_were_topped_with_capitals_in_the_form_of_a_double_bull%2C_Persepolis%2C_Iran_%2847779521811%29.jpg/170px-thumbnail.jpg" decoding="async" width="170" height="257" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/The_stone_columns_of_the_Gate_of_All_Nations%2C_they_were_16%C2%BD_meters_high_and_were_topped_with_capitals_in_the_form_of_a_double_bull%2C_Persepolis%2C_Iran_%2847779521811%29.jpg/255px-thumbnail.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/The_stone_columns_of_the_Gate_of_All_Nations%2C_they_were_16%C2%BD_meters_high_and_were_topped_with_capitals_in_the_form_of_a_double_bull%2C_Persepolis%2C_Iran_%2847779521811%29.jpg/340px-thumbnail.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3264" data-file-height="4928" /></a><figcaption>The stone columns of the <a href="/wiki/Gate_of_All_Nations" title="Gate of All Nations">Gate of All Nations</a>, they are 16½ meters high and were topped with capitals in the form of a double bull.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Gate_of_All_Nations" title="Gate of All Nations">Gate of All Nations</a>, referring to subjects of the empire, consisted of a grand hall that was a square of approximately 25&#160;m (82&#160;ft) in length, with four columns and its entrance on the Western Wall.
</p>
<ul class="gallery mw-gallery-packed">
