<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Apadana_Palace_coin_hoard">Apadana Palace coin hoard</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Persepolis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Apadana Palace coin hoard"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<div class="thumb tmulti tright"><div class="thumbinner multiimageinner" style="width:454px;max-width:454px"><div class="trow"><div class="theader">Apadana hoard</div></div><div class="trow"><div class="tsingle" style="width:166px;max-width:166px"><div class="thumbimage"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:KINGS_of_LYDIA._Time_of_Cyrus_to_Darios_I._Circa_545-520_BC.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/KINGS_of_LYDIA._Time_of_Cyrus_to_Darios_I._Circa_545-520_BC.jpg/164px-KINGS_of_LYDIA._Time_of_Cyrus_to_Darios_I._Circa_545-520_BC.jpg" decoding="async" width="164" height="67" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/KINGS_of_LYDIA._Time_of_Cyrus_to_Darios_I._Circa_545-520_BC.jpg/246px-KINGS_of_LYDIA._Time_of_Cyrus_to_Darios_I._Circa_545-520_BC.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/KINGS_of_LYDIA._Time_of_Cyrus_to_Darios_I._Circa_545-520_BC.jpg/328px-KINGS_of_LYDIA._Time_of_Cyrus_to_Darios_I._Circa_545-520_BC.jpg 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="329" /></a></span></div><div class="thumbcaption text-align-center">Gold <a href="/wiki/Croeseid" title="Croeseid">Croeseid</a> minted in the time of <a href="/wiki/Darius_I" class="mw-redirect" title="Darius I">Darius</a>, of the type of the eight Croeseids found in the Apadana hoard, <abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span style="white-space:nowrap;">&#8201;545–520 BC</span>. Light series: 8.07&#160;g (0.285&#160;oz), <a href="/wiki/Sardis" title="Sardis">Sardis</a> mint.</div></div><div class="tsingle" style="width:130px;max-width:130px"><div class="thumbimage"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Aegina_Stater_achaic.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Aegina_Stater_achaic.jpg/128px-Aegina_Stater_achaic.jpg" decoding="async" width="128" height="68" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Aegina_Stater_achaic.jpg/192px-Aegina_Stater_achaic.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Aegina_Stater_achaic.jpg/256px-Aegina_Stater_achaic.jpg 2x" data-file-width="706" data-file-height="377" /></a></span></div><div class="thumbcaption text-align-center">Type of the <a href="/wiki/Aegina" title="Aegina">Aegina</a> stater found in the Apadana hoard, 550–530<span class="nowrap">&#160;</span>BC. Obverse: <a href="/wiki/Sea_turtle" title="Sea turtle">Sea turtle</a> with large pellets down centre. Reverse: incuse square punch with eight sections.<sup id="cite_ref-ACH29_46-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ACH29-46">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup></div></div><div class="tsingle" style="width:152px;max-width:152px"><div class="thumbimage"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:THRACE,_Abdera._Circa_540-35-520-15_BC.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/THRACE%2C_Abdera._Circa_540-35-520-15_BC.jpg/150px-THRACE%2C_Abdera._Circa_540-35-520-15_BC.jpg" decoding="async" width="150" height="68" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/THRACE%2C_Abdera._Circa_540-35-520-15_BC.jpg/225px-THRACE%2C_Abdera._Circa_540-35-520-15_BC.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/THRACE%2C_Abdera._Circa_540-35-520-15_BC.jpg/300px-THRACE%2C_Abdera._Circa_540-35-520-15_BC.jpg 2x" data-file-width="500" data-file-height="228" /></a></span></div><div class="thumbcaption text-align-center">Type of the <a href="/wiki/Abdera,_Thrace" title="Abdera, Thrace">Abdera</a> coin found in the Apadana hoard, <abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span style="white-space:nowrap;">&#8201;540/35–520/15 BC</span>. Obverse: Griffin seated left, raising paw. Reverse: Quadripartite incuse square.<sup id="cite_ref-ACH29_46-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ACH29-46">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup></div></div></div></div></div>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Apadana_hoard" title="Apadana hoard">Apadana hoard</a> and <a href="/wiki/Achaemenid_coinage" title="Achaemenid coinage">Achaemenid coinage</a></div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Apadana_hoard" title="Apadana hoard">Apadana hoard</a> is a hoard of coins that were discovered under the stone boxes containing the foundation tablets of the <a href="/wiki/Apadana_Palace" class="mw-redirect" title="Apadana Palace">Apadana Palace</a> in Persepolis.<sup id="cite_ref-ACH29_46-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ACH29-46">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> The coins were discovered in excavations in 1933 by <a href="/wiki/Erich_Schmidt_(archaeologist)" title="Erich Schmidt (archaeologist)">Erich Schmidt</a>, in two deposits, each deposit under the two deposition boxes that were found. The deposition of this hoard is dated to <abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span style="white-space:nowrap;">&#8201;515 BC</span>.<sup id="cite_ref-ACH29_46-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ACH29-46">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> The coins consisted in eight gold lightweight <a href="/wiki/Croeseid" title="Croeseid">Croeseids</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Tetradrachm" title="Tetradrachm">tetradrachm</a> of <a href="/wiki/Abdera,_Thrace" title="Abdera, Thrace">Abdera</a>, a stater of <a href="/wiki/Aegina" title="Aegina">Aegina</a> and three double-<a href="/wiki/Sigloi" class="mw-redirect" title="Sigloi">sigloi</a> from <a href="/wiki/Cyprus" title="Cyprus">Cyprus</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-ACH29_46-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ACH29-46">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> The Croeseids were found in very fresh condition, confirming that they had been recently minted under Achaemenid rule.<sup id="cite_ref-CHI_50-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CHI-50">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup> The deposit did not have any <a href="/wiki/Daric" title="Daric">Darics</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sigloi" class="mw-redirect" title="Sigloi">Sigloi</a>, which also suggests strongly that these coins typical of <a href="/wiki/Achaemenid_coinage" title="Achaemenid coinage">Achaemenid coinage</a> only started to be minted later, after the foundation of the Apadana Palace.<sup id="cite_ref-CHI_50-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CHI-50">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="The_Throne_Hall">The Throne Hall</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Persepolis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: The Throne Hall"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Hall_of_Hundred_Columns_(Throne_Hall)_in_Persepolis.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Hall_of_Hundred_Columns_%28Throne_Hall%29_in_Persepolis.jpg/220px-Hall_of_Hundred_Columns_%28Throne_Hall%29_in_Persepolis.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="146" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Hall_of_Hundred_Columns_%28Throne_Hall%29_in_Persepolis.jpg/330px-Hall_of_Hundred_Columns_%28Throne_Hall%29_in_Persepolis.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Hall_of_Hundred_Columns_%28Throne_Hall%29_in_Persepolis.jpg/440px-Hall_of_Hundred_Columns_%28Throne_Hall%29_in_Persepolis.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4928" data-file-height="3264" /></a><figcaption>The Throne Hall, Persepolis</figcaption></figure>
<p>Next to the Apadana, second largest building of the Terrace and the final edifices, is the Throne Hall or the Imperial Army's <i>Hall of Honor</i> (also called the <i>Hundred-Columns Palace</i>). This 70&#160;m<sup>2</sup> ×&#160;70&#160;m<sup>2</sup> (750&#160;sq&#160;ft ×&#160;750&#160;sq&#160;ft) hall was started by <a href="/wiki/Xerxes_I" title="Xerxes I">Xerxes I</a> and completed by his son <a href="/wiki/Artaxerxes_I_of_Persia" class="mw-redirect" title="Artaxerxes I of Persia">Artaxerxes I</a> by the end of the fifth century BC. Its eight stone doorways are decorated on the south and north with reliefs of throne scenes and on the east and west with scenes depicting the king in combat with monsters. Two colossal stone bulls flank the northern portico. The head of one of the bulls now resides in the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Chicago_Oriental_Institute" class="mw-redirect" title="University of Chicago Oriental Institute">Oriental Institute</a> in Chicago<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup> and a column base from one of the columns in the <a href="/wiki/British_Museum" title="British Museum">British Museum</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>At the beginning of the reign of Xerxes I, the Throne Hall was used mainly for receptions for military commanders and representatives of all the subject nations of the empire. Later, the Throne Hall served as an imperial museum.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="The_Tachara_Palace">The Tachara Palace</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Persepolis&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: The Tachara Palace"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p><a href="/wiki/Tachara" title="Tachara">Tachara</a>, was the exclusive palace of <a href="/wiki/Darius_the_Great" title="Darius the Great">Darius the Great</a> at Persepolis. Only a small portion of the palace was finished under his rule, it was completed after the death of Darius in 486 BC, by his son and successor, <a href="/wiki/Xerxes_I" title="Xerxes I">Xerxes</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup> who called it a Taçara, which means "winter palace" in Old Persian. It was then used by <a href="/wiki/Artaxerxes_I" title="Artaxerxes I">Artaxerxes I</a>. In the 4th century BC, following his invasion of Iran in 330 BC, <a href="/wiki/Alexander_the_Great" title="Alexander the Great">Alexander the Great</a> allowed his troops to loot Persepolis. This palace was one of the few structures that escaped destruction in the burning of the complex by Alexander's army, and because of that, Tachara is the most intact building of Persepolis today. It is also the oldest structure at Persepolis. Tachara stands back to back to the <a href="/wiki/Apadana" title="Apadana">Apadana</a>, and is oriented southward.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul class="gallery mw-gallery-packed">
